+{"id":"coding_agent_session_search-k0bzk","title":"bug: cass health recommended_action tells users to run index --full during active rebuild (stampede advice)","description":"Discovered during ibuuh.10.6 (bead v0p2i) test authoring. Comparing cass status --json and cass health --json with a seeded rebuild-active state:

CASS STATUS (correct):
  recommended_action = "Index rebuild is already in progress"
  -- implemented at src/lib.rs::run_status line ~11785: `if rebuild_active { ... }`

CASS HEALTH (buggy, stampede advice):
  recommended_action = "Run 'cass index --full' to rebuild the index/database."
  -- at src/lib.rs::run_health line ~12051, the selector falls through to the !healthy branch at ~12056 because `healthy = !(... && !rebuild_active && ...)`. The conditional at 12051 checks `not_initialized` and `db_degraded` but forgets to check `rebuild_active` first.

Both surfaces also set their respective active-rebuild flag correctly (`rebuild.active=true` in status, `rebuild_progress.active=true` in health), so the buggy recommendation is not because cass failed to detect the rebuild -- it's a missing branch in the text selector.

Repro: see v0p2i probe flow -- seed `.lexical-rebuild-state.json` + hold `index-run.lock` exclusively, then call `cass health --json`. `recommended_action` comes out as the stampede advice.

Fix: add an `if rebuild_active { Some("Index rebuild is already in progress".to_string()) }` arm at the top of the run_health recommended_action selector (line ~12051), mirroring run_status.

Impact: agents polling cass health during a long rebuild will see "run cass index --full", attempt to kick a second run, and either lock-stampede (retryable error) or -- worse -- actually start a concurrent pipeline depending on lock acquisition path.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T03:30:54.648207029Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-24T03:30:54.648207029Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-k25j6","title":"Wire STYLE_PILL_ACTIVE into filter pill rendering","description":"## Goal
Restore high-signal filter-chip affordances by wiring STYLE_PILL_ACTIVE as true per-pill chip styling (not flat row text).

## Why This Matters
Users rely on active filters to understand search scope at a glance. Flat text weakens affordance clarity and causes missed context.

## Required Implementation
- Replace generic STYLE_TEXT_PRIMARY usage in active-pill rendering with semantic token-driven chip styling.
- Refactor pill rendering so each active pill is rendered as its own styled span/chip unit.
- Preserve existing click-target geometry and interaction behavior (last_pill_rects) exactly.

## Explicit Decision
- Whole-row background styling can be used only as a short-lived intermediate spike.
- Definition of done requires per-pill chip styling (individual chip backgrounds), not a row-level approximation.

## Tests (Mandatory)
1. test_pill_row_uses_pill_active_token
2. test_pill_active_has_background
3. test_pill_row_empty_uses_muted
4. test_pill_mouse_targets_preserved
5. cassapp_search_with_filters.snap (or equivalent focused snapshot)

## Logging/Diagnostics Expectations
- Test output must include scenario identifiers and active-filter sets for failures.
- Snapshot diffs should clearly indicate pill-level styling regressions.

## Acceptance
- Active filters render as visually distinct chips per pill
